{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Groups like Koch Industries and the Center for American Progress, usually bitter adversaries, are banding together to reduce prison populations and overhaul sentencing.", "abstract": "Conservative conglomerate Koch Industries and liberal issues institute Center for American Progress are jointly backing Coalition for Public Safety, new organization working to fix criminal justice system; coalition, which will host advocacy campaigns to reduce prison populations and overhaul sentencing, among other initiatives, hopes to set example for Congress by showing how bipartisan groups can achieve consensus policy.", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Carl", "role": "reported", "lastname": "HULSE", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By CARL HULSE", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/19/us/politics/unlikely-cause-unites-the-left-and-the-right-justice-reform.html", "lead_paragraph": "Groups like Koch Industries and the Center for American Progress, usually bitter adversaries, are banding together to reduce prison populations and overhaul sentencing.", "headline": {"main": "Unlikely Cause Unites the Left and the Right: Justice Reform", "print_headline": "On Criminal Justice, the Right and the Left Meet in the Center"}, "_id": "54e54e6f38f0d82d01cf7608", "word_count": "949", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/02/19/us/19CRIMINALJP1/19CRIMINALJP1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/02/19/us/19CRIMINALJP1/19CRIMINALJP1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2015/02/19/us/19CRIMINALJP1/19CRIMINALJP1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/02/19/us/19CRIMINALJP1/19CRIMINALJP1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"he